v1.30.7 - SECURITY: SSRF guard on webhook URLs (S-11)

A user with webhooks.manage could create a webhook pointed at
127.0.0.1, 169.254.169.254 (cloud metadata), updater:9000, or any
RFC 1918 host on the compose network. On every matching event the
backend POSTed the team payload + HMAC headers, turning TaskHub into
an SSRF probe into otherwise unreachable infrastructure.

Fix:
- New lib/ssrfGuard.ts uses ipaddr.js (added as a runtime dep) to
  classify addresses into named ranges. Refuses loopback, private
  (RFC 1918), link-local (INCLUDES 169.254.169.254 metadata), CGN,
  reserved, unspecified, broadcast, multicast, plus IPv6 loopback,
  unique-local, link-local. IPv4-mapped IPv6 (::ffff:10.0.0.1) is
  detected and the underlying IPv4 re-classified - the classic SSRF
  bypass.
- HTTP/HTTPS schemes only. file://, gopher://, ftp:// are refused at
  the scheme check.
- Hostnames are resolved via dns.lookup({ all: true }); ANY internal
  A/AAAA record refuses.
- Operator escape hatch: WEBHOOK_ALLOWED_HOSTS env, comma-list,
  default empty. Exact hostname match (no CIDR / wildcard) for
  deliberate internal receivers.
- Two-point enforcement: WebhookService.create + update (when URL
  changes) for fast admin feedback; WebhookService.deliverOnce
  re-resolves before EVERY fetch to defend against DNS rebinding.
  Delivery refusal marks the row failed with the guard reason - no
  HTTP request leaves the backend.

15 new tests in webhookSsrf.test.ts: unit-level classifier coverage
(7 cases including the 169.254.169.254 cloud-metadata IP and the
::ffff:10.0.0.1 IPv4-mapped IPv6 bypass), create endpoint refusal
(7 cases for various private targets + a sanity check that the
explicitly allow-listed 127.0.0.1 still creates), and a delivery
refusal that mutates the URL in the DB to simulate DNS rebinding.

tests/setup.ts sets WEBHOOK_ALLOWED_HOSTS=127.0.0.1 so the existing
receiver-stub tests in apiTokensAndWebhooks.test.ts keep working. The
new tests use 127.0.0.2 / 192.168.x / 10.x / 169.254.x / [::1] /
[::ffff:10.x] so the guard's refusal IS exercised.

Phase boundary:
- Allow-list is literal hostname match - no CIDR, no wildcard.
  Documented; operators add each host explicitly.
- fetch() does its own DNS lookup after our guard returns; a racy
  attacker could theoretically slip a bad address between them.
  Pinning the address via a custom undici dispatcher is a v1.31+
  follow-up.
- ipaddr.js is the first new runtime dep since v1.27.

Verified: tsc clean. webhookSsrf.test.ts 15/15.
apiTokensAndWebhooks.test.ts 15/15. Full suite 309 passed, 5 skipped
(LDAP), 1 pre-existing backups order-flake (passes in isolation).